tweet: The specificity and durability advantages of siRNAs over ASOs wouldn't be relevant if siRNAs couldn't target nuclear DMPK mRNA for DM1. $RNA shows they can indeed knockdown nuclear mRNA, albeit at lower efficiencies than cytoplasmic mRNA. https://t.co/jTIMBEkbqK

name: snicobio
tweet: Unlike siRNAs, ASOs aren't loaded into a ribonucleoprotein complex and likely exhibit a half-life more similar to free siRNA. Both siRNAs and ASOs are chemically-modified. Why it matters: $RNA's AOC may be dosed quarterly and $DYN's ASO may be dosed monthly. Huge differentiation.

name: snicobio
tweet: The liver and kidney are natural reservoirs for ASOs, and therefore would likely be off-targets or therapeutic sinks for a muscle-directed therapy. You can see this off-target effect in the $DYN preclinical data. $RNA also achieves greater mRNA knockdown vs. $DYN at lower doses. https://t.co/jOo6qOq9Fu

name: snicobio
tweet: $RNA's choice in siRNA revolves around specificity and durability. In terms of specificity, siRNAs form much weaker non-specific interactions with plasma and cell surface proteins compared to ASOs, and therefore can be more efficiently and specifically directed to muscle cells.

name: snicobio
tweet: $RNA is utilizing an siRNA mechanism to target mutant DMPK mRNA. This was actually very confusing to me at first because I had learned that siRNAs primarily work in the cytoplasm, whereas ASOs primarily work in the nucleus. Why did $RNA choose siRNA when Art is an ASO expert?

name: snicobio
tweet: This sequestering of MBNL alters the splicing profiles of important muscle-related RNAs, leading to the progression of DM1. Eliminating mutant DMPK mRNA in the nucleus addresses the root cause of the disease, making ASOs/siRNAs a particularly attractive MOA.
